================================================================================
HOW TO BUILD AND RUN
================================================================================

REQUIREMENTS
------------
    - GCC compiler (tested on iLab with gcc)
    - GNU Make
    - All source files in the same directory

BUILDING
--------
To compile, run:

    make

This produces the following executable:

    mysh        — a simple command-line shell supporting interactive and batch modes

To remove all compiled files and start fresh:

    make clean


RUNNING THE SHELL
-----------------
Interactive mode (run directly in a terminal):

    ./mysh

Batch mode with a script file:

    ./mysh script.sh

Batch mode via pipe:

    cat script.sh | ./mysh


RUNNING THE TEST SUITE
----------------------
    ./test_mysh.sh

No arguments needed. Runs all automated tests across tokeniser, built-ins,
wildcards, executor, redirection, pipes, and syntax error recovery.

You may need to grant execute permission first:

    chmod +x test_mysh.sh

================================================================================
DESIGN NOTES
================================================================================

OVERVIEW
--------
This project implements mysh, a simple UNIX shell that supports interactive and
batch execution modes. It reads commands line by line, tokenises and parses them,
expands wildcards, and executes them using fork/execv with support for I/O
redirection and pipelines.

FILES + PURPOSES
----------------

================================================================================
FILE: mysh.c
================================================================================

Purpose: core shell implementation. Handles mode detection, the main read-parse-
execute loop, and all shell functionality. Structured in the following stages:

    1. print_prompt:    prints the cwd-based prompt in interactive mode,
                        replacing the HOME prefix with ~ where applicable.

    2. tokenise:        splits a line into tokens. '>', '<', '|' are always
                        single-character tokens. '#' starts a comment and
                        discards the rest of the line.

    3. expand_wildcard: expands a single glob token (containing '*') into the
                        sorted list of matching filenames in the target directory.
                        Hidden files are excluded when the pattern starts with '*'.
                        If no files match, the token is passed through unchanged.

    4. expand_tokens:   walks the full token list and calls expand_wildcard on
                        any token containing '*'.

    5. is_builtin:      returns 1 if a name matches one of the four built-in
                        commands: cd, pwd, which, exit.

    6. find_program:    searches /usr/local/bin, /usr/bin, /bin (in that order)
                        for a bare program name. Returns a malloc'd path or NULL.

    7. parse:           splits the expanded token list into a subcmd_t array,
                        one entry per pipeline stage separated by '|'. Assigns
                        redir_in and redir_out for each stage. Returns -1 and
                        prints an error on syntax errors.

    8. run_builtin:     implements cd, pwd, which, exit directly in the shell
                        process. cd uses chdir(), pwd uses getcwd(), which
                        searches the same directories as find_program, exit
                        signals the main loop to terminate.

    9. spawn:           forks a child process for one pipeline stage. Sets up
                        stdin/stdout via dup2() for file redirection and pipe
                        ends. Uses /dev/null as default stdin in batch mode.
                        Calls execv() for external programs, or run_builtin()
                        for built-ins participating in a pipeline.

    10. main:           determines mode (interactive vs batch) via isatty(),
                        runs the read-tokenise-expand-parse-execute loop,
                        handles exit and syntax error recovery, and prints
                        welcome/goodbye messages in interactive mode.

================================================================================
FILES: arraylist.h, arraylist.c
================================================================================

Purpose: dynamic array of char* strings, carried over and extended from Project 2.
Used to build argv lists and wildcard match sets. Contains:

    1. al_init:          allocate and initialise an arraylist.
    2. al_destroy:       free all stored strings and the array itself.
    3. al_length:        return current number of elements.
    4. al_push:          append with deduplication (used for file lists).
    5. al_push_nocheck:  append without deduplication (used for argv/token lists).
    6. al_pop:           remove and return the last element.
    7. has_word:         return 1 if a string is present (uses strcmp).

================================================================================
FILES: linestream.h, linestream.c
================================================================================

Purpose: buffered line reader over a file descriptor using read() only.
Carried over from Project 2. Critical for the spec requirement that read()
is not called again until the current command has been fully executed.
Contains:

    1. lines_init:    initialise the reader for a given file descriptor.
    2. lines_next:    return a pointer to the next newline-terminated line,
                      growing the buffer if needed. Returns NULL at EOF.
    3. lines_destroy: free the internal buffer.

================================================================================
ALGORITHM: mysh main loop
================================================================================

    Step 1: Determine mode. If one argument given, open it and use BATCH mode.
    If no argument, use isatty() to choose INTERACTIVE or BATCH.

    Step 2: In interactive mode, print welcome message. Enter the main loop.

    Step 3: In interactive mode, print the prompt (cwd with ~ abbreviation).

    Step 4: Read one line via lines_next(). If NULL (EOF), break.

    Step 5: Tokenise the line. Skip empty and comment-only lines.

    Step 6: Expand wildcard tokens in place.

    Step 7: Parse the expanded token list into a subcmd_t array. On syntax
    error, print a message, free resources, and continue to next line.

    Step 8: Check if any subcmd is 'exit'. If so, set should_exit flag.

    Step 9: Execute:
        - Single built-in with no pipeline: run inline via run_builtin(),
          handling any output redirection with dup2().
        - Everything else: iterate over subcmds, create pipes between
          adjacent stages, spawn a child per stage, then waitpid() for all.
          Report non-zero exit status or signal termination in interactive mode.

    Step 10: Free subcmd argvs and tokens. If should_exit, break the loop.

    Step 11: Print goodbye message in interactive mode. Clean up and exit.

================================================================================
TEST PLAN
================================================================================

test_mysh.sh

All tests are run in batch mode (piped input or script file) so that output
can be captured and compared automatically.

SECTION 1: Tokeniser + Wildcard
    Verifies that comment lines produce no output, inline comments are stripped,
    empty lines are skipped, and that commands execute correctly after tokenising.

SECTION 2: Built-ins
    Tests each built-in command individually:
    - pwd: prints the current working directory.
    - cd: no-arg (goes to HOME), absolute path, relative path, nonexistent
      directory (error message), too many arguments (error message).
    - which: finds ls and grep, returns nothing for builtins, nonexistent
      programs, and wrong argument counts.
    - exit: stops the loop so subsequent commands do not run.

SECTION 3: Wildcard Expansion
    Verifies that glob patterns expand to sorted matches, hidden files are
    excluded, no-match tokens pass through unchanged, and multiple wildcards
    in one command each expand independently.

SECTION 4: Script File + Exit Codes
    Verifies multi-command scripts run correctly, exit mid-script stops
    processing, comment-only scripts produce no output, bad script paths
    return EXIT_FAILURE, and valid inputs return EXIT_SUCCESS.

SECTION 5: Executor - External Commands
    Verifies that external programs (ls, ls -a) run correctly, unknown
    commands print an error message, and absolute paths execute directly.

SECTION 6: Redirection
    Verifies output redirection (>) creates and populates a file, input
    redirection (<) reads from a file, and output redirection truncates
    an existing file.

SECTION 7: Pipes
    Verifies single pipes, pipes into wc -l, two-pipe chains, and built-in
    commands (pwd, which) participating in pipelines via piped output to cat.

SECTION 8: Syntax Error Recovery
    Verifies that syntax errors (< < and bare >) print an error message but
    the shell continues executing subsequent commands rather than crashing.

================================================================================
ERROR HANDLING
================================================================================

    1. Syntax errors in parse() print a message to stderr and skip to the
       next command; the shell continues running.
    2. File open failures for redirection print a perror message; the child
       exits with status 1.
    3. Unknown program names print "<name>: command not found" to stderr.
    4. cd failures use perror to report the OS error.
    5. The shell itself always exits with EXIT_SUCCESS except when it cannot
       open its script file argument.

================================================================================
KNOWN LIMITATIONS
================================================================================

    1. The spec permits assuming that '>', '<', and '|' are separated from
       other tokens by whitespace, so tokens like '>file' are not handled.

    2. Redirection is not supported inside pipeline sub-commands (per spec).

    3. A maximum of 4096 pipeline stages is supported, since we use an array for storage.

    4. ls . and ls .* behave in somewhat different ways than the normal shell. Since
       . is interpreted as the present directory when there is only 1 dot in the argument,
       they will print the full directory